    <div class="research-content">
        <div style="padding: 1.5rem;">
            <p>The first paper I worked on as an RA focuses on intersectional wage discrimination and the concept of excessive privilege. We examined the effects of overlapping identities on wage gaps, particularly the intersectional effects of gender and race in the US labor market.</p>
            
            <p>Key findings from our research:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>We discovered that White males (WM) experience unique privilege compared to all other groups, which we termed "excessive White male privilege".</li>
              <li>Contrary to previous literature, we did not find evidence for a unique intersectional wage penalty for Black females (BF) compared to all others.</li>
              <li>Our findings challenge common methods of measuring intersectional wage discrimination and highlight the importance of recognizing and addressing systemic privilege.</li>
            </ul>
          
            <div class="graph-container">
              <img src="intersectionality_graph.png" alt="Graph showing privilege and intersectional penalty terms over time" class="responsive-graph"/>
              <figcaption>Results for the privilege and intersectional penalty term for both reference groups. Data uses average wages in the US from the Economic Policy Institute.</figcaption>
            </div>
          
            <p>This research provides a novel tool for intersectionality studies and policy aimed at creating a more equitable society. It emphasizes the need for more refined metrics in capturing wage discrimination and the importance of considering excessive privilege in analyses of wage gaps.
            </p>
